subsection.p:
Given a curve \mathcal{C} in \mathbb{R}^n, parameterized by \mb{r}: [a, b] \to \mathbb{R}^n, and a scalar function f on it, the most common notation for a scalar integral is
\int_{\mathcal{C}} f ( \mb{r} ) \, \tder{}{s} \amp = \int_{\mathcal{C}} f \vol^X, \amp = \int_a^b f ( \mb{r} (t) ) \| \mb{r}^\prime (t) \| \, \tder{}{t}
Such an integral on a curve is called a scalar line integral. This formula follows immediately from equation . Students may question why the letter s is used in the \tder{}{s} notation. This is because s is often used as an arc-length parameter for the curve.
